Too many different colors of green; choose a more concise palette and then stick with it. The menu items on the top left probably shouldn't not be gradiented because they don't clearly indicate their functionality. A better choice would be to have them all be consistent color when not moused-over and then turn a different shade when an individual one IS moused-over. Finally, what's up with the background being a gradient itself? There are more than enough gradients on the page already, it feels reallllly overboard.

The design looks good.  The different sections are clearly separate, the links are easy to read and stand out against their background, the whole thing is not too cluttered.  The color scheme matches the college, and it's easy to tell what college the site is about.  I'm not what improvements could be made here.

The main focal point of the picture is nice, but having more students (perhaps of all different ethnicities) would be beneficial and provide a more inclusive vibe to prospective and current students. The overall layout of the webpage is nice, and offers easily accessible links to various things a student or staff member might need. I like the 'in the news' and 'campus events' sections, as this will give prospective students something to click on to get to know the college better, and get a better feel for what happens around campus.

This is a solid design with a good layout that looks like it'd let me find what I need (from admissions info to staff emails to class schedules) pretty easily. 

On the sidebar there are two advertisements for visiting the college ("Coming to Parkland? Get started here!" and "GO Ahead! Visit us!" One such advertisement is probably sufficient and could either be larger (reducing clutter) or replaced with something else. Finally, the bottom sections on the left side advertising "As You Like It" clashes badly with the overall color scheme/theme; it's not awful but it looks out of place. As a fan of Shakespeare I definitely think it's worth advertising, but perhaps it could be done in a way that merged better with the page's overall look and feel.
I think there should be a link to tuition and fees.  There also may be too much green.

The left side looks a little bit cluttered, especially on the bottom. The "need extra credit hours" and Shakespeare boxes could be replaced with something else, even some blank space or design to make the page look less cluttered and more elegant. The lists on the bottom right could be more exciting; the colors and lists look a little dull. Perhaps for the "in the news" section just have one big picture related to the most recent story that gives the title when you hover over it. People can click on "in the news" to read more headlines if they wish. The campus events could possibly be replaced with an actual calendar or something other than a plain list.
